description:
Habitat: This plant was found growing around the trunk of a large tree. The tree was the last tree at the edge of the forest and and shaded over everything. The plant grew from the ground, up the side of the tree reaching at least 15 feet up the trunk of the tree and onto a branch.

Identification: This plant had the typical vine structure of a Virginia Creeper. It also had the same five spiraled leaf pattern that is seen in the example photos on iNaturalist, as well as similar leaf morphology and venation. This observation was identified as Virginia Creeper by other iNaturalist users.

Habitat: This plant was found at the very edge of a forest. It was the tallest plant of the variety of plants within two feet of the edge of the forest. Being the tallest, the plant was able to get plenty of sunlight.

Identification: This plant matched the native region as described, and also had similar leaf venation as the iNaturalist example photos. The three-lobed leaf morphology also matched the example photos. This entry was confirmed as Sassafras by others as well on iNaturalist.

Habitat: This plant was found at the edge of a forest. It was surrounded by a lot of underbrush. Many vines and small plants were around with shrubs of various sizes a few meters away. There were some other plants of the same species near by. Plant received a lot of sunlight in the late morning through evening as the canopy of the forest was on the opposite side of the sun.

Identification: This plant had the same vertical structure as often described. It did not have the typical golden yellow flowers that are described as it was too late in the season for its flowers. This plant did have very similar leaf morphology and leaf venation as the photos on iNaturalist. The presence of multiple plants of this species matched the description of the Canada Goldenrod being an invasive plant species.

Habitat: This tree was medium sized and found about 4 feet from the edge of a forest on the top of a slope. A small creek was at the bottom of the slope and the soil appeared somewhat rocky. These black spots were found over many of the leaves of this Norway maple tree.

Identification: These black spots match iNaturalist photos for the tar spots that are made by this parasitic fungus (R. acerinum). The black spots were found in September and the Black Tar Spot is known for appearing in the late summer and Autumn. The spots are also commonly infecting maples, and the host was a Norway maple. Another user also identified these spots as Black Tar Spots.

Habitat: Was one of a cluster of shrubs at the edge of a small forest. Not the largest shrub but larger than most. Located at the top of a small slop from a small creek.

Identification: This plant was a broad shrub like the Japanese Barberry is described. It had identical leaf morphology and leaf venation compared to iNaturalist photos and had the typically described fruits. The fruits had similar shape and were in the abundance generally described and in iNaturalist photos. It was taken too early in the season for the fruits to be red as photos often show.

This was in a dry, elevated place that was not covered by trees. However, it was growing about 40m from a water logged area, and also relatively close to a road. It is autumn, so the coloration may be derived from these changes. Pinnately compound leaves with linear venation. Stem was no more than 6 cm tall before node growths. Red and hairy stem. https://www.thespruce.com, characterizes the species for living in a swampy area, which is where this plant dwells. It has a smooth leaf edge around it, and the leaves also have a much lighter color along the venation.

description: This plant was naturally occurring with minimal plants growing around it. It was in low competition with the nearby wildlife growing in the shade of a temperate forest. It grew about 50-60 meters from a fresh water source. Had a height of 1.5 meters tall, and had a diameter (farthest branch tip on opposing sides) of about 60cm. The plant appeared to have these woody, symmetrical growths jutting out from four sides of the plant stem. These are marked as a defining characteristic for the Euonymus, as well as a preference for a moist environment and the tolerance of light exposure or shade on https://www.ecolandscaping.org. Interestingly, they are a rare invasive species which has escaped cultivation. They are traditionally from Asia!

description: The habitat of this tree was found in Worcester, Ma at Assumption College exposed in the natural sunlight, grown in moist, dirt soil. Sun and rain was directly hitting the plant, and only the back of the scrub was covered by shade. The scrub was located outside, near a body of water. The soil of the scrub contained other green leaves, signifying the same species in a different color or a different species. The plant was near other similar looking scrubs, as well as being on a college campus, signifying an urban atmosphere. The shrub is most likely cultivated, as it placed on the campus. This plant is most likely a euonymus alatus, or winged euonymus. This species can also be referred to as the "burning bush" as shown in the bright pink leaves. This species is native to China, Japan, Korea, so it is cultivated in Worcester, Ma. The species is part of the Celastraceae family. It is also an angiosperm and eudicot. The scrub is deciduous and is much wider than tall. The bright pink leaves have an acute apex, as shown in the photos.

This plant was naturally growing next to a electrical divot, which contained a multitude of colonies growing along the plant. It was a very damp area, and water was logged inside of the trench/divot. The Hornwort was growing 5.5cm radially, and had protrusions ("horns") that were at maximum 4cm. According to https://www.britannica.com, they are characterized by presence of the thallus, looking like a continuation of a waxy, flat tissue that sits at the foot of the protrusion in the plants. These can be confused with liverworts, which have a slightly different point of junction with sporophytes.

This was found in a damp environment close to the forest tree line, and about 20 meters out from a water source. The moss was stout, short, and had a radius of about 20cm. The plant was marked by leaf-like appendages, which is commonly associated with Selaginella genus. This was identified by community member on the site. Futher, they are characterized with the presence of strobilus (small branch-like emergence from the stem which contain  modified leaves) and rhizophores which transition into rhisomes and protrude from various nodules in the plant stem (not just the bottom), according to site http://www.biologydiscussion.com.

description: Grew on the shaded side of a tall tree (In the summer afternoon). Leaf arrangement varied. Leaf shape varied (see picture 6/6). Had brown stem with hairy protrusions adhering it to the tree (see picture 4/6).
Grew in the middle of a lawn/field. 3 leaves cake out at the top of each stem except the one with the browning purple flower. Hairy stem and hairy bottom of the leaves. Hairs were very tiny and white

This plant was observed to be growing on the edge of a wooded area behind a building on the Assumption College campus. This plant has full access to sunlight due to being on the edge of the wooded area and has full access to rain water. This plant has five leaves in a whirled pattern around the stem and the leaves are growing to be about 7 cm long. The entire plant is about 15 cm  off the ground. This plant has a crenate leaf margin. The suggested plant ID of the plant is to be Parthenocissus quinquefolia, Parenthenocissus inserta, or parthenocissus tricuspidata. 

Parthenocissus quinquefolia is common to Missouri. This plant looks very similar to the observed plant but seems to be growing both close to the ground and very tall off the ground. This plant has a whirled pattern and is similar to the observed plant. 

Parenthenocissus inserta is common to Eastern North America. This plant has the same amountof leaves as in the observed plant, however the leaves are thicker than in the observed plant. 

Parthenocissus tricuspidata is common to Asia, Japan, and China. This plant does not look similar tot he morphology of the observed plant. This plant seems to have one leaf with a parted margin, compared to five leaves being whirled around the stem.

This plant was growing off the side of the road headed into a wooded area. Where this plant is located has plenty of access to sunlight and rain water, with a creek nearby. This plant has a lanceolate shape and a parted margin. This plant grows close to the ground, at about 15 cm long. The leaves are about 9 cm long. The suggested ID of the plant is either Onoclea sensibilis, Phegopteris connectilis, or Osmunda claytoniana. 

Onoclea sensibilis is common to North America and ranges in a wide variety of states. This plant does look very similar to the observed plant. It has both the parted and similar leaf shape. This plant however does seem to grow a little taller than the observed plant. 

Phegopteris connectilis is common to North America, Europe, and Asia. This plant has similar leaf margin and shape, howeevr it is arranged differently than in the observed plant. The leaves in this plant point in all directions instead of just straight out from the branch. 

Osmunda claytoniana is common to Missouri. This plant also looks very similar to the morphology of the observed plant, however grows in a more upward direction than in the observed plant.

description: The green frog is a secondary consumer, eating anything from spiders, to crayfish, to insects, to other frogs. Green frogs are most obviously recognized by the bright green sides of their heads. They typically have a dark green or brown back, although this coloring can be varied. In order to distinguish the green frog from the bullfrog, one can look at the ridged lines on the frogs back, called glandular folds. On bullfrogs these lines circles around the ear, on green frogs they go straight down the back. Green frogs begin as eggs, before hatching quickly in about a week. They are then tadpoles, with a tail and no legs, before becoming a froglet, which has legs and a tail. Finally, the frog sheds the tail, and becomes a mature adult. The frog observed is a mature adult. I was not able to sex it. Green frogs are found around inland water sources, such as a stream, creak, lake, or pond. They can also be found in deep mud when hibernating, and in damp woods near water. A predator of the green frog is the Northern Water Snake, a competitor is the American Bullfrog.

description:
The Black Oak is native to Eastern North America and apart of the Quercus genus within the Fagaceae family. The lobes of the leaf, typically there are seven, are sharply pointed and are key to identifying the tree. Its inner bark is an orange-yellow color, making it a source of tannin and quercitron which are yellow dyes.

Reference: https://www.britannica.com/plant/black-oak

The Northern Red Oak is native to Eastern North America and is a part of the Quercus genus within the Fagaceae family. Much like the Black Oak the leaves of the Northern Red Oak have seven pointed lobes. They appear to be dark green in the summer and turn red and brown in the fall. The Northern Red Oak is statistically the most valuable timber per acre as stated by the New England Forestry Foundation, however it is much less abundant than trees like White Pine, which is used more often for furniture and flooring because of its abundance.

Reference: https://newenglandforestry.org/2019/05/16/meet-the-northern-red-oak/

The Multiflora Rose is native to Eastern Asia, making it an invasive species, and a part of the Rosa genus within the Rosaceae family. This invasive plant can be identified by its thicket growth pattern, small clusters of fruits, and its elliptical sharply toothed leaflets. Multiflora Rose was first introduced to North America around the 1860s for rose breeding; around the 1930s its spread was encouraged by the USDA as a form of soil erosion control. As of 2009, the state of Massachusetts prohibited the importation, distribution, trade, and sale of Multiflora Rose. Its dense thicket can take over an area and prevent native plants from spreading as well as prevent some native birds from nesting. It has no effective predators and grows exceptionally quick. Repeated mowing is suggested, establishing that once cut the area will have to be mowed regularly to prevent the regrowth of Multiflora Rose.

Reference: https://www.kingcounty.gov/services/environment/animals-and-plants/noxious-weeds/weed-identification/multiflora-rose.aspx
https://www.ecolandscaping.org/07/landscape-challenges/invasive-plants/multiflora-rose-an-exotic-invasive-plant-fact-sheet/

The Northern Catalpa is native to the Southern United States but can also be found in the Northeast, it is a part of the Catalpa genus within the Bignoniaceae family. The leaves of the Northern Catalpa grow to a very large size and tend to enjoy warmer humid environments. The leaves are heart sharped and are oppositely aligned. The Northern Catalpa blooms white and yellow flowers in the spring. Due to their flowers they are very advantageous for honeybees and other pollinators.

Reference: https://www.mortonarb.org/trees-plants/tree-plant-descriptions/northern-catalpa
https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=casp8

The Norway Maple is native to Europe and Western Asia, making it an invasive species, and a part of the Acer genus within the Sapindaceae family. The leaf has a palmate shape with pointed lobes. It was first introduced to North America from England as an ornament plant in the 1700s, some desired it for its shade cover that it creates with its dense canopy. However, this dense canopy is now an issue to native plants in New England. Norway Maples reproduce in short proximity to each other, causing rapid displacement of native tree and shrubs. Its dense shade covering prevents the growth of other native plants within its vicinity. It is also thought that the Norway Maple produces toxins that prevent the growth of possible native competitors although this has not been proven scientifically.  It is suggested to not plant Norway Maple and to cut down existing trees. Better native substitutes such as the Sugar Maple or the Red Maple are suggested.

Reference: https://www.invasive.org/alien/pubs/midatlantic/acpl.htm

description: American Bullfrogs are secondary consumers, eating almost everything including insects, tadpoles, other frogs including the spring peeper, and even other bullfrogs. They are the largest of the north american frog species, and have a very distinct rumbling grunt for a call. They are typically greenish brown, and lack dorsal ridges, which distinguishes it from the green frog. The underside may have dark spots. The life cycle of a bullfrog begins with an egg, and then developing into a tadpole. After that stage, legs develop which transforms the tadpole into a froglet. After the froglet stage, the tail is lost, and it becomes a mature frog. The individual I heard was a mature adult frog. I was not able to sex it because I could not see the circles under the eyes. I assume that it was male because of the loud vocalization. The habitat of the American Bullfrog is aquatic, and they can be found in small ponds, creeks, rivers, streams, and other wet environment. They can also be found in marshlands and swamps. A predator of the bullfrog is the snapping turtle. A competitor of the bullfrog is the green frog.

description: This dragonfly is a secondary consumer, eating a variety of flying insects including small moths. This dragonfly has yellow legs with clear wings, with a small cloudy part near the base of the wing. The coloring is dependant on sex, with males having a bright red abdubon, and females haveing a more sbduded yellowish brown abduman. Both females and males have a brownish face and thorax. The life cycle of this dragonfly begins as eggs in an aquatic environment. Then, they become naiads, a stage that lives in an aquatic environment. After sufficient development in the naiad stage, they emerge as adult dragonflies. The dragonfly I observed was an adult male. The Autumn Meadowhawk lives in and near streams, lakes, and ponds. It can often be found flying nearby water, and requires water for reproduction. A potential predator of these dragonflies is large mouth bass, which eat them as they lay eggs on the surface of water. Prey includes the common mayfly. A competitor is the purple martin, which also eats mosquitoes.

The western honey bee is a primary consumer, eating the pollen and nectar from flowers. The western honey bee is smaller than a bumblebee, and can be identified by the presence of many many hairs around their heads and eyes. These are used to collect pollen. The body of mature western honey bees is yellow, with four black stripes. The black tends to be concentrated at the posterior of the bee body. It thrives in a large range of habitats, from tropical forests to taigas. The nests they form are built to hold more than 6,000 bees, and can be found hanging from houses, trees, shrubs, railings, and many other places. The western honey bee has been introduced all over the world, and often thrives, proving its habitat universality. This bee pictured here is an adult. This bee was gathering pollen, so it is a male. Bees begin as eggs, and then hatch for an eight day larval stage in which they feed heavily. After the larval stage, they create a wax pupa, and then eat through it to emerge as young bees. A predator for bees is vespine wasps in southeast Asia.

Monarch butterflies are primary consumers, eating milkweed plants as caterpillars. Monarchs are very distinctly colored yellow and black. They are easily identifiable by the specific black patterning on the wings. It is a fairly large butterfly, with the wingspan of three to four inches. The life cycle of a monarch  butterfly starts as an egg, then moves into a larva stage, also known as the caterpillar. After the larva stage, they grow into a pupa, also called a chrysalis. Eventually, they emerge as adults in their butterfly stage. The individual I observed was an adult, and I was not able to sex it. Monarchs live in open fields and meadows, populated with milkweed plants. Tachinid fly larvae acts as a parasite   and can overtake the pupa stage to feed off of the monarch. The prey for monarchs is milkweed plants. Monarchs feed exclusively on milkweed plants, so they don't have many competitors. However they do compete with milkweed bugs.

The bicolored sallow is a primary consumer, with the caterpillar eating leaves of many trees. It is identified primarily by the two-toned aspects of its wings, which are typically brown and then darker brown towards the tips. However, this moth can vary in color. One distinctive aspect of the bicolored sallow is the dark band at the bottom of the wing, with a small dark spot often present in the middle of the wing. The thorax is fuzzy and brown. The life cycle of the bicolored sallow begins as an egg, which then becomes a caterpillar before molting into a moth. The individual see here is a mature adult. I was not able to sex it. The bicolored sallow has a very wide range, occurring in both Mexico and Canada. They eat the leaves of trees, so having woody areas is a must for this moth. This moth eats the leaves of oak trees, and one predator of the bicolored sallow is the big brown bat, which is common in MA. A competitor of this moth is the forest tent caterpillar, which also eats oak tree leaves.

description: The eastern carpenter bee is a primary consumer, eating pollen and nectar from flowers. The Eastern carpenter is a large bee species, which differentiates it from most bee species besides the bumblebee.  However it can be differentiated from the honey bee by its shiny black abdomen, and its distinctive purple tint. The middle body is yellow with a black dot. Eastern carpenter bees begin as eggs, and then develop into larva and pupa stages. Although the eggs are laid at different times, the eggs laid later develop faster, so they hatch all at the same time. After the pupa stage, the bees emerge as adults, and can fly after three or four days. The indivdual I saw was an adult.  It was a female, as males have a white spot on thier heads. The habitat of the eastern carpenter bee is widespread. They live throughout the eastern coast of the USA, and up into Canada. They nest in wood, so they will be close to a wooded area, and they eat pollen and nectar, so their habitat must also have flowers of some kind. They also nest in wooded structures such as houses. The prey of the bee is the nectar and pollen of plants, such as showy goldenrod. A competitor of the eastern carpenter bee is the eastern honey bee. A parasite of it is the tiger bee fly, which infects the larva.

description: The dark paper wasp is a primary consumer, eating the nectar or sugar made from the nectar of the flowers. Dark paper wasps have a primarily black body, with yellow stripes on the abdomen. They typically have a long and slender body, which distinguishes it from the yellow jacket, which it is often mistaken for. They also tend to fly with their stinger pointed down, not out as other stinging insects do. Paper wasps start out as eggs, all laid by a single queen in a nest. Then, they turn into larvae, and eat insects brought to them by adult members of the community. Soon after entering the larval stage, they transition into the mature adult stage, which is pictured here. I was not able to sex it. Dark paper wasp nest can be found hanging from tree branches or shrubs, and can also be found on the eaves and hanging from the roofs of homes. Dark paper wasps eat the nectar of flowers as adults, and as larvae they are eating by badgers.

description:
The Common Eastern Bumble Bee is a primary consumer.

An Eastern Bumble Bee has yellow "fur-like" hairs, with a shiny black bald spot on its thorax. It is also much larger in size than other bees such as the honeybee. Another distinguishing factor is that it has a furry abdomen, while carpenter bees do not. 

Bumble Bees are born in nests underground. The larvae hatch during the summer, and live for about a month.

This one is full grown so it is an adult.

As worker bumble bees are female this is likely a female.

Eastern Bumble Bees can be found all over New England. They live in nests underground and can be found in fields or other areas with lots of angiosperms.

A competitor would be the honeybee, with a potential predator would be a field mouse.

Order Hemiptera, the ringed assassin bug is a secondary consumer, eating small insects such as mosquitoes and other bugs. It can be identified by the distinctive white and black banded legs. It also has a dull or bright orange body with black markings on the side of it. It can be distinguished from similar looking insects by the wings and lack of abdominal spines. The ringed assassin bug has a three stage life cycle: egg, nymph, and adult. After hatching from an egg, it takes around two months for the nymph to transition into being an adult, and several molts. The individual I saw was an adult. I was not able to sex it. Assassin bugs live near forests, meadows, fields, and brush. Typically, these bugs are observed further south, but recently have been pushed north due to climate change. One competitor for the ringed assassin bug is the blue eyed darner butterfly, which also eats mosquitoes, and a predator is the house sparrow, who eats bugs.
